Insurance—Underwriting
Our management views our insurance businesses as possessing two distinct activities – underwriting and investing.
Underwriting decisions are the responsibility of the unit managers, while investing decisions are the responsibility of Berkshire’s
Chairman and CEO, Warren E. Buffett and Berkshire’s corporate investment managers. Accordingly, we evaluate performance of
underwriting operations without any allocation of investment income or investment gains and losses. We consider investment
income as an integral component of our aggregate insurance operating results. However, we consider investment gains and losses,
whether realized or unrealized, as non-operating. We believe that such gains and losses are not meaningful in understanding the
periodic operating results of our insurance businesses.
The timing and magnitude of catastrophe losses can produce significant volatility in our periodic underwriting results,
particularly with respect to our reinsurance businesses. Generally, we consider incurred losses exceeding $100 million from a
current year catastrophic event to be significant. The significant catastrophe events in 2021 included Hurricane Ida and floods in
Europe in the third quarter, as well as Winter Storm Uri in the first quarter.
Changes in estimates for unpaid losses and loss adjustment expenses, including amounts established for occurrences in prior
years, can also significantly affect our periodic underwriting results. Unpaid loss estimates, including estimates under retroactive
reinsurance contracts, were approximately $125 billion as of December 31, 2021. Our periodic underwriting results may also
include significant foreign currency transaction gains and losses arising from the changes in the valuation of non-U.S. Dollar
denominated liabilities of our U.S. based insurance subsidiaries due to foreign currency exchange rate fluctuations.
